  "prompt": "Do you use Java or JavaScript to make an Android game?",
  "response": "For Android game development, you typically use Java or Kotlin. Here's a breakdown:\n\n1. Java:\n- Traditionally the primary language for Android development\n- Widely used and has extensive support\n- Works well with Android SDK\n- Good for beginners with Android game development\n\n2. Kotlin:\n- Modern language officially supported by Google for Android\n- More concise and expressive than Java\n- Fully compatible with Java\n- Increasingly popular for Android development\n\nAlternatives:\n- C++ (with Android NDK) for high-performance games\n- Game engines like Unity (uses C#) or Unreal (uses C++)\n- Frameworks like LibGDX (Java-based)\n\nJavaScript is not typically used directly for native Android game development, though it can be used in hybrid app frameworks like React Native or for web-based games.",
